    <subsection>
        <title>Graphing a Line in Slope-Intercept Form</title>

        <p>We will start with a video lecture as an overview.</p>

        <figure><video youtube="XwyMlLpWVS0" width="70%" /></figure>

        <p>To graph the line <m>y=3x+5\text{,}</m> we could build a table (the general method to graph any equation):</p>

        <table>
            <caption>Table for <m>y=3x+5</m></caption>
            <tabular>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                    <cell><m>x</m>-values</cell>
                    <cell><m>y</m>-values</cell>
                    <cell>Points</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>y=3(-2)+5=-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(-2,-1)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>y=3(-1)+5=2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(-1,2)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>y=3(0)+5=5</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(0,5)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>y=3(1)+5=8</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(1,8)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>y=3(2)+5=11</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(2,11)</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>Next, we plot each point, connect them, extend both ways, and get the graph. Today we will learn an easier way to graph a line in slope-intercept form.</p>

        <list>
            <title>Graphing a Line in Slope-Intercept Form</title>
            <ol>
                <li>Graph the <m>y</m>-intercept, which is at <m>(0,b)\text{.}</m> For <m>y=3x+5\text{,}</m> the <m>y</m>-intercept is at <m>(0,5)\text{.}</m></li>
                <li>Starting at the <m>y</m>-intercept, draw a slope triangle to reach the next point. For <m>y=3x+5\text{,}</m> we draw a slope triangle with base <m>1</m> and height <m>3\text{,}</m> reaching <m>(1,8)\text{.}</m></li>
                <li>Draw slope triangles in both directions, finding more and more points on the line. Connect all points and extend both ways.</li>
            </ol>
        </list>

        <sidebyside>
            <caption>Three Steps to Graph a Line in Slope-Intercept Form</caption>
            <figure>
                <caption>Step 1</caption>
                <image>
                <description>This is a Cartesian grid with (0,5) plotted.</description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            xmin=-2,xmax=4,ymin=-1,ymax=18,
                            minor ytick=,
                            xtick={-1,0,...,5},ytick={2,5,...,17}
                        ]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 5)} node[above left] {$(0,5)$};
                        \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <figure>
                <caption>Step 2</caption>
                <image>
                <description>This is a Cartesian grid with (0,5) plotted. There is a slope triangle from (0,5) to (1,5), and then to (1,8). The point (1,8) is also plotted.</description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            xmin=-2,xmax=4,ymin=-1,ymax=18,
                            minor ytick=,
                            xtick={-1,0,...,5},ytick={2,5,...,17}
                        ]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 5)} node[above left] {$(0,5)$};
                            \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,5) (1,5) (1,8)};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1, 8)} node[above left] {$(1,8)$};
                            \node at (axis cs: 0.5,5) [below] {$1$};
                            \node at (axis cs: 1,6.5) [right] {$3$};
                        \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <figure>
                <caption>Step 3</caption>
                <image>
                <description>This is a Cartesian grid with (0,5) plotted. There is a slope triangle from (0,5) to (1,5), and then to (1,8). The point (1,8) is also plotted. There is a slope triangle from (1,8) to (2,8), and then to (2,11). The point (2,11) is also plotted. There is a slope triangle from (2,11) to (3,11), and then to (3,14). The point (3,14) is also plotted. There is a slope triangle from (-1,2) to (0,2), and then to (0,5). The point (-1,2) is also plotted.</description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            xmin=-2,xmax=4,ymin=-1,ymax=18,
                            minor ytick=,
                            xtick={-1,0,...,5},ytick={2,5,...,17}
                        ]
                            \addplot[
                                domain = -2:4,
                                <->,
                                smooth,
                                thin,
                                color = red,
                            ]{3*x+5};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 5)} node[above left] {$(0,5)$};
                            \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,5) (1,5) (1,8)};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1, 8)} node[above left] {$(1,8)$};
                            \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(1,8) (2,8) (2,11)};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,11)};
                            \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-1,2) (0,2) (0,5)};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,2)};
                            \node at (axis cs: 0.5,5) [below] {$1$};
                            \node at (axis cs: 1,6.5) [right] {$3$};
                            \node at (axis cs: 3,14) [above left, color=red] {$y=3x+5$};
                        \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

        </sidebyside>
    </subsection>

