    <subsection>
        <title>Writing Linear Equations based on Graph</title>

        <p>We will start with two video lectures as an overview.</p>

        <table>
            <tabular>
                <col/>
                <col/>
                <row>
                    <cell><video youtube="mmWf_oLTNSQ" width="70%" /></cell>
                    <cell><video youtube="FhyanLhqdjk" width="70%" /></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>We just learned how to graph a linear equation given in slope-intercept form. Going back in the other direction, we can write a linear equation based on its graph.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>According to the graph, find the line's equation in slope-intercept form.</p>
                <figure>
                    <image>
                    <description>This is a Cartesian grid with a red line, which passes (0,6), (2,4), (4, 2), (6,0), ...</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[
                                xmin=-2,xmax=8,ymin=-2,ymax=10,
                                minor ytick=,
                                xtick={-1,0,...,7},ytick={-1,0,...,9}
                            ]
                            \addplot[
                                domain = -2:8,
                                <->,
                                smooth,
                                thin,
                                color = red,
                            ]{-0.5*x+6};
                            \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>On the line, we will pick two points with integer coordinates. Note that we can pick any two points, and will find the same slope.</p>

                <figure>
                    <image>
                    <description>This is a Cartesian grid with a red line, which passes (0,6), (2,4), (4, 2), (6,0), ... The points (0,6) and (2,4) are plotted. A slope triangle is drawn from (0,6), passes (4,6) and ends at (4,2). Its base is labeled "4-0=4", and its height is labeled "2-6=-4".</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[
                                xmin=-2,xmax=8,ymin=-2,ymax=10,
                                minor ytick=,
                                xtick={-1,0,...,7},ytick={-1,0,...,9}
                            ]
                            \addplot[
                                domain = -2:8,
                                <->,
                                smooth,
                                thin,
                                color = red,
                            ]{-0.5*x+6};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,6)} node[below left] {$(0,6)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,4)} node[below] {$(4,4)$};
                            \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,6) (4,6) (4,4)};
                            \node at (axis cs: 2,6) [above] {$4-0=4$};
                            \node at (axis cs: 4,5) [right] {$4-6=-2$};
                            \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>By the slope triangle, we can calculate the line's slope:<me>\text{slope}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{-2}{4}=-\frac{1}{2}</me></p>

                <p>From the graph, we can see the <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,6)</m></p>

                <p>With the slope and <m>y</m>-intercept found, we can write the line's equation:<me>y=-\frac{1}{2}x+6</me></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

