    <subsection>
        <title>Applications of Slope-Intercept Form Equations</title>

        <p>We can model real-life data with slope-intercept equations in many situations. We will start the lesson with a video lecture as an overview.</p>

        <figure><video youtube="XJEG94UkfbM" width="70%" /></figure>

        <p>Next, we will look at a few examples.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>A cab company charges <dollar/><m>4.50</m> per trip, plus <dollar/><m>1.25</m> per mile. Use a liner equation to solve the following problems.<ol>
                    <li>How much is the fare if a trip is <m>27</m> miles long?</li>
                    <li>If a person has <dollar/><m>100</m> in his pocket, how long a trip can he afford?</li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The rate of change (slope) is <dollar/><m>1.25</m> per mile, and the starting value (<m>y</m>-intercept) is <dollar/><m>4.50\text{.}</m> To model this scenario, we can use this slope-intercept linear equation:<me>y=1.25x+4.5</me>In this equation, <m>x</m> stands for the number of miles in a trip, and <m>y</m> stands for the amount of money to be charged.</p>

                <p>If a trip is <m>27</m> miles long, we substitute <m>x</m> in the equation with <m>27\text{,}</m> and we have:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=1.25x+4.5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=1.25(27)+4.5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=33.75+4.5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=38.25</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p><em>Solution for Part 1:</em> A trip <m>27</m> miles long would cost <dollar/><m>38.25\text{.}</m></p>

                <p>Next, to find how long a trip would cost <dollar/><m>100\text{,}</m> we substitute <m>y</m> in the equation with <m>100\text{,}</m> and solve for <m>x</m>:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=1.25x+4.5</mrow>
                        <mrow>100\amp=1.25x+4.5</mrow>
                        <mrow>100\mathbf{{}-4.5}\amp=1.25x+4.5\mathbf{{}-4.5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>95.5\amp=1.25x</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{95.5}{1.25}\amp=\frac{1.25x}{1.25}</mrow>
                        <mrow>76.4\amp=x</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p><em>Solution for Part 2:</em> <dollar/><m>100</m> can afford a trip <m>76.4</m> miles long.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>In a certain reservation, there are approximately <m>2,400</m> African elephants. Unfortunately, the population has been decreasing by 30 heads per year. Use a liner equation to solve the following problems.<ol>
                    <li>If the trend continues, what would the elephant population be 15 years later?</li>
                    <li>If the trend continues, how many years later would the elephant population dwindle to <m>1,200\text{?}</m></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The rate of change (slope) is <m>-30</m> per year, and the starting value (<m>y</m>-intercept) is <m>2400</m> heads. To model this scenario, we can use this slope-intercept form linear equation:<me>y=-30x+2400</me>In this equation, <m>x</m> stands for the number of years, and <m>y</m> stands for the elephant population.</p>

                <p>To estimate the elephant population 15 years later, we substitute <m>x</m> in the equation with <m>15\text{,}</m> and we have:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-30x+2400</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-30(15)+2400</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-450+2400</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=1950</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p><em>Solution for Part 1:</em> If the trend continues, there would be <m>1,950</m> elephants on this reservation 15 years later.</p>

                <p>Next, to find when the elephant population would decrease to <m>1,200\text{,}</m> we substitute <m>y</m> in the equation with <m>1200\text{,}</m> and solve for <m>x</m>:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-30x+2400</mrow>
                        <mrow>1200\amp=-30x+2400</mrow>
                        <mrow>1200\mathbf{{}-2400}\amp=-30x+2400\mathbf{{}-2400}</mrow>
                        <mrow>-1200\amp=-30x</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{-1200}{-30}\amp=\frac{-30x}{-30}</mrow>
                        <mrow>40\amp=x</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p><em>Solution for Part 2:</em> If the trend continues, <m>40</m> years later, the elephant population would dwindle to <m>1,200\text{.}</m></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>

