    <subsection>
        <title>Finding a Line's Equation with Two Points</title>

        <p>Since two points can determine a line's location, with two given points on a line, we can determine a line's equation. We will learn how to do that in this section. Here are two video lectures as an overview.</p>

        <table>
            <tabular>
                <col/>
                <col/>
                <row>
                    <cell><video youtube="P1ex_a6iYDo" width="70%" /></cell>
                    <cell><video youtube="3RV0jC5eK-4" width="70%" /></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
        
        <p>Next, we will look at an example.</p>

        <p><em>Scenario:</em> A spa chain has been losing customers at a roughly constant rate since the year 2000. In 2005, it had <m>2,975</m> customers; in 2011, it had <m>2,585</m> customers. Management estimated that the company will close once its customers decrease to <m>2,000\text{.}</m> If this trend continues, when will the company close?</p>

        <p>Since the company's number of customers has been decreasing at a constant rate, we can model this situation with a linear equation, <me>y=mx+b</me>where <m>x</m> stands for the number of years since 2000, and <m>y</m> stands for the number of customers. We need to find the value of <m>m</m> (slope) and <m>b</m> (<m>y</m>-intercept).</p>

        <p>By the given conditions, we have two points on the line: <m>(5,2975)</m> and <m>(11,2585)\text{.}</m> We will use the slope formula to find the slope. After labeling those two points as <m>(\overset{x_1}{5},\overset{y_1}{2975}) \text{ and } (\overset{x_2}{11},\overset{y_2}{2585})\text{,}</m> we have:<md>
                <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=\frac{2585-2975}{11-5}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=\frac{-390}{6}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-65</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        

        <p>The slope implies the company has been losing approximately <m>65</m> customers per year since 2000. Now the equation looks like <me>y=-65x+b</me>The point <m>(5,2975)</m> implies: In the equation <m>y=-65x+b\text{,}</m> when <m>x=5\text{,}</m> <m>y=2975\text{.}</m> We will substitute <m>x</m> with <m>5</m> and <m>y</m> with <m>2975\text{,}</m> and we have:<md>
                <mrow>y\amp=-65x+b</mrow>
                <mrow>2975\amp=-65(5)+b</mrow>
                <mrow>2975\amp=-325+b</mrow>
                <mrow>2975\mathbf{{}+325}\amp=-325+b\mathbf{{}+325}</mrow>
                <mrow>3300\amp=b</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>Now we have the equation <m>y=-65x+3300\text{,}</m> we can substitute <m>y</m> with <m>2000</m> to find when the number of customers will decrease to <m>2000\text{:}</m><md>
                <mrow>y\amp=-65x+3300</mrow>
                <mrow>2000\amp=-65x+3300</mrow>
                <mrow>2000\mathbf{{}-3300}\amp=-65x+3300\mathbf{{}-3300}</mrow>
                <mrow>-1300\amp=-65b</mrow>
                <mrow>\frac{-1300}{-65}\amp=\frac{-65x}{-65}</mrow>
                <mrow>20\amp=x</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>The answer implies that the number of customers will decrease to <m>2,000</m> in the year 2020, and that's when the company will close if the trend continues.</p>

    </subsection>

